Architects have understood that offices also need childcare.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say it also hides inside a small childhood with everything to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose study numerous well-known buildings in Brno came out, thought of the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardianship.
In the company, around 90 people work, mainly at the age of baby boom and wanted to allow architects and delineators to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, childcare is one of the benefits Arch.Design offers to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the opportunity to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guardian was an idea of Arch.Designu’s employees themselves and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-guardianship of the company is funded through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as from the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a grant of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When financing is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the mini-guardianship in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the financing application contributed the company Economy Rating.
Children’s attention is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, they are present all day for their care a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education. Childcare currently welcomes children without age limits, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since this is a "mini-guardian," it can only simultaneously accommodate a maximum of five children, although with their turns they come more throughout the day.
The operation of the childcare is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the childcare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guardian program are comparable to the usual pre-school teaching program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach English to English.
The class has not only toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of small children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the employer and his employer.
Thus, Arch.Design is located amongst companies that signed that offer a huge advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced staff marketing.
The bone house continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the loop of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its form similar to a skeleton, the locals called it "the bone house".
Its organic shapes, its flashing colors, the new use of the stone, the tiles and mosaic fragments, a facade that reminds the scales and all-present gently curved lines, all of this is typical of Antoni Gaudí’s secession.
The cover of the house plays with onyric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated so that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpent and torsion of forms continue to surprise us also inside.
The wavy wood copies the frames of the windows, barrels, ornaments of the doors, mirrors and letters.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the animated shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, emerged from the renovation of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on breaking down the previous building and starting from zero, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the House Batlló, made up of various apartments, did not design it Antoni Gaudí alone.
He collaborated in the design by architect Josep María Jujol.
In fact, on their project plans, adornments arose for the representative apartment of the property owner and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Park Güell de Gaudí, where other pieces are found there.
Because of its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion called it "the bone house".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the boasts".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, pattern of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation respirators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange forty-five degree inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction standards of the moment and was not allowed to influence them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, the municipality was so impacted by the result it requested to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public staircase.
The arrangements were never carried out, rather on the contrary: only fifteen days after the municipality request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
In the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
On the second floor gallery was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all the angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can be communicated in this way without a problem, without renouncement of the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior patio and lights.
The game with the two colors provides the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sun rays.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and more recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the buhardilla, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, reaching €16.50, although students, retirees and tourist cards holders get 20% off.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
