A longer index finger than the annular indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than the annular are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British journal on cancer.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
“Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age,” said Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
Accordingly, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles indicates.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and simultaneously 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the indic finger of the right hand shorter than the ring.
They had the same chances of suffering from prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
In the case of men with a longer index than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60%, the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined during the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but he doesn’t seem that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer can be “demonstrated completely.”
