It continues to increase support for democracy in Latin America as well as support for private companies.
Crime causes greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it allows for monitoring attitude changes in the region.
In the results of this year’s survey, conducted in September and early October, two related issues highlight.
The first is the relatively animated humor in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% annually since 2002, democracy support has increased from reduced 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It grew also in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the surveyed in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which reduces the regional average (see graph 2).
About 44% of respondents in the region declared satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than 25% recorded in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% claimed that they trusted their country’s Congress and 45% in their government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than 2003 (17% and 24%, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulences in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it had remained during the global financial crisis was probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Furthermore, the existence of a stronger social security network has contributed to protecting the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and that it has decreased again this year, up to 32 percent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic yields and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, are reflected in a general feeling of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, instead of unemployment, as the most serious problem your country faces (see graph 5).
About 31% claim that, whether they or a nearby relative, they have been the victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has been reduced since 38% last year and that is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
Most positive economic yields are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56% (see graph 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow your country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of respondents in Venezuela think the same (and 80% support private companies), although their left president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises greater leadership in the region, as indicates 19% of respondents (from 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% versus 11% one year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela has such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
