An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it proves that there are possible forms of life without the main elements they considered essential.
“This body has a double capacity.”
"It can grow with phosphorus or arsenic."
“This makes it something very peculiar, although little is missing to be a really ‘alien’ type of lifestyle,” said Paul C. W. Davies from Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears on Thursday’s online edition of Science.
For a long time, there are six major elements that are essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing the phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar from Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
As Anbar said, the find is important for the search for life on different planets than Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, know how it looks.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated great speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report to indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery shows is that in other planetary environments, there may be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of “standard” elements that we consider to be indispensable for life may not be so fixed,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University at Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is novel because it demonstrates the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and basic biochemistry structure,” Cockell added.
The discovery was not done by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA’s astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because he has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to phosphorus.”
"Consequently, it can be complicated for organisms to differentiate them."
“However, the arsenic is different enough to not work as well as the phosphorus, so it enters and, in some way, appeals the biochemical machinery,” Anbar explains.
The researchers collected bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but demonstrating that it can live with arsenic instead poses the possibility that naturally a form of life that uses arsenic may exist, whether in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where the arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an auxiliary professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic can be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early eras of Earth, he said, so researchers speculated that the first forms of life may have used it.
“Yes, it suggests that there might be other ways to generate life, not only the way life formed on Earth formerly,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
