Can Civism tender a bridge to unite the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invictive and negativity, this week a little civism has been triggered in Washington.
Is it a preach of a genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusorian moment before a quick turn to the partisan fight in the capital?
The meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders on Tuesday did not produce any progress on the big issues to be dealt with during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences of the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to win partisan points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that exceeds the ideological gap that still separates members.
That's just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a test period, surveying each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to assess the boundaries of public opinion and voters’ patience for a renewed partisan warfare.
Reason for which the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and are very deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it comes to taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, both parties are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to how to say things,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections awaken supporting passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
In some matters, particularly those listed in the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax reductions are winning at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment grants, probably because Republicans cannot believe they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, deniing unemployment grant for unemployed.
After the White House meeting on Tuesday, there is greater optimism for a possible deal with these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START nuclear disarmament treaty (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institute, warns that successful cooperation in the urgent issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanity when the new 112th Congress gathers in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement begins.
“After things to be done are carried out, psychology will return the situation to a confrontation in the short term,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and voters of the Tea Party, which decisively contributed to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders have awareness of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to meet their promises to cut state expenses and cancel the new health law.
These supporting lines are already clearly observed in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, including the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the expenditure cut.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have brought the issue of deficit in the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the commission of 18 members to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected in the panel, suggesting that in tax issues there are at least few basis or desire for commitment today.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of supporting shocks, when the Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and medical assistance, then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would the change cause?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partism of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead point, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of people.
Anyone who thinks he’s losing will probably change course and seek commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partitism and polarization are currently greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological hole between Obama and Congress Republicans than was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, both parties activists see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort from both sides to find points in common on issues that still divide them.
