“For them, life under the Red Jemers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is generating divisions within families.”
During the government of the Cambodia Red Jemers, between 1975 and 1979, they were executed or died of hunger, illness or excess work, about 1.7 million people.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government led by Pol Pot, the remains of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodia border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement took over in December 1998.
Like Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
