Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while waiting for the process.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest fighters of the Red Jemers fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite officials of the Red Jemers retained their local administrative positions in exchange for laying their weapons, the raw soldiers remain poor and non-qualified farmers.
