EU changes rules to get visa
People must go to Visa Applicants Service Centers prior to their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa will be changed at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants must visit Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC) prior to their interview at the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the biometric information of the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for the applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer need to make a payment to conclude the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another for the messaging service delivered the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: equivalent to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for requested visa cases (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for merchants and investors visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will submit their documents and take their footprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Also, those applying for visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
