Avenger Hackers and Diligent Spies
The WikiLeaks matter has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandal to the hypocrisy that governs relationships between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound international changes and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is formed exclusively by press cuts.
The “extraordinary” U.S. revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs reflect only what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Khadafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule according to which secret files should only be formed by public knowledge news is essential for the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to seek news about the inexistent), but because those who devote occultism not only trust what they already know, which reaffirms what they had already learned.
This is Dan Brown’s success mechanism.
The same applies to secret files.
The reporter is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little desire) the head of secret services (if he could not be, I know what, editor of the Liberation), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent the U.S. embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as published the Newsweek last week.
So why have the revelations of these files caused such revolt?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, i.e., that embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of states can call themselves by phone or take the plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited exercises of representation, have turned into spionage centers.
Any viewer who watches research movies knows it perfectly, only we seem that we don’t know it for hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secrets of the world’s most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the “verdugos”.
But let’s enter the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, at the time of Orwell, he could be conceived to all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, able to control each movement thanks to the phone, each transaction carried out, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the cryptographs of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the venger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can you endure a power that can no longer and cannot keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is a empty secret (and a empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge of Berlusconi’s character or Merkel is actually a empty, unsecret secret, since it comes from the public area; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has made, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets.
WikiLeaks has not hurt Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is obvious that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it on a street poster.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, it cannot be expected to keep confidential conversations by phone.
Nothing is easier than discovering whether and when a Head of State has moved by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly that for the moment, my forecast is a science fiction thing and therefore a novel, but I imagine government agents who distract discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, like a lot, hiding some data written in their shoes.
That information is then retained, in a single copy, in closed drawers with keys: in the end, the Watergate’s attempt to spy was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances as a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wireless (telephone) telegraph.
The video tapes (analogical) had allowed cinema researchers to study a movie step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now CDs (digitals) only allow forward or backward from chapter to chapter, i.e., to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the displacements it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of normal that policy and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
A last comment.
Olderly, the press tried to understand what was secretly worked in embassies.
Today, embassies are asking for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's promises of financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French hooks have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $3 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute €7.2 billion in three years and France €1.260 billion (i.e. €420 billion a year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast-start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a great complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what is really worth: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which places it on the right path towards meeting its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made without harming official development aid.
Unfortunately, you have not reached an agreement on what it means “new and additional”.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, each one chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken reference to 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years are added as a fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of “all new projects” of 2010 is “new and additional.”
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditures of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, France's total amount of aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it aims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, believe that each borrowed euro is equivalent to a donated euro.
Of course, such a thing is difficult to justify: effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain cost-effective investments (often, projects related to emission reduction based on more effective technologies), it is fake to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a donated euro... As much as, only the cost of the loan to the country that grants the loan should be computed for its commitments (ities equivalent).
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see for its own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments to 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union brings a euro to fulfill its commitment, France only brings ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions in time and, on the other, in relation to true financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been busy with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other Member States were going to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The early funding chapter is a short-term detail in relation to the entire climate negotiations.
But it might be a more sand grain in the vast machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of complying with its commitments and the same way as the rest of the European Union.
But, especially, France could make the debates on gambling bets advance in terms of long-term financing (another essential chapter currently discussed): we will not get rid of the issue of the "additional trace" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive in relation to this matter as it is with others.
Therefore, we have left the hope of the new Minister of Environment, Mrs. Kosciusko-Morizet, to arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France’s fast start and its vision of the “additional trace” and the use of loans would contribute to improving the level of international confidence necessary to advance the negotiations.
